<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[189,303,1485,1511]" box="[189,303,1485,1511]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1485,1511]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1485,1511]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[189,1399,1531,1698]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Although only a single specimen of 
<taxonomicName authority="Morassi &amp; Nappo &amp; Bonfitto, 2017" authorityName="Morassi &amp; Nappo &amp; Bonfitto" authorityYear="2017" box="[616,810,1531,1558]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Otitoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="elegans" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[616,810,1531,1558]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Otitoma elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[817,908,1532,1558]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is available, this species differs distinctly from its described congeners in having only a few, widely-spaced primary spiral cords with well developed secondary spiral sculpture, and a peculiar color pattern (yellowish-white with brown-orange spiral cords). 
<taxonomicName authority="Morassi &amp; Nappo &amp; Bonfitto, 2017" authorityName="Morassi &amp; Nappo &amp; Bonfitto" authorityYear="2017" box="[359,489,1637,1663]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Otitoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="elegans" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[359,489,1637,1663]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">O. elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[501,596,1637,1663]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
further differs from its congeners of similar size in possessing a paucispiral and domed protoconch instead of multispiral and conical.
</paragraph>
